    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA228-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi ciṟaippuṟamākat talaimakaṭkuc colluvāḷāyt talaimakaṉ kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said so that HE would hear, being one who speaks to HER when [he] was behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA228">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            eṉṉeṉap paṭumō tōḻi miṉṉuvaci</l>
<l>            patirkura leḻili mutirkaṭaṉ ṟīrak</l>
<l>            kaṇṭūrpu virinta kaṉaiyiru ṇaṭunāṭ</l>
<l>            paṇpi lāriṭai varūu nantiṟat</l>
<l>            taruḷāṉ kollō tāṉē kāṉavaṉ </l>
<l>            ciṟupuṟaṅ kaṭukkum peruṅkai vēḻam</l>
<l>            veṟikoḷ cāpat teṟikaṇai verīi</l>
<l>            yaḻuntupaṭa viṭarakat tiyampu</l>
<l>            meḻuntuvī ḻaruviya malaikiḻa vōṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>What can be said, friend?<note place="foot">The same formulaic beginning is to be found in KT 194.1.</note></l>
<l>Does he not have [any] consideration for us,</l>
<l rend="indent">coming along [this] bad difficult way at midnight in deep darkness</l>
<l rend="indent2">that spread for the eyes to be filled, while the clouds with a shaking voice</l>
<l rend="indent3">fulfill their age-old duty, flashes<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains the <term xml:lang="ta">miṉṉu</term> here not as the verbal root, but as a special form of <term xml:lang="ta">sandhi</term> for the noun <term xml:lang="ta">miṉ</term> which definitely would be preferable (for a parallel cf. <term xml:lang="ta">puḷḷu</term> for <term xml:lang="ta">puḷ</term> in NA 78.9).</note> splitting?</l>
<l>– the master of the mountain of waterfalls descending from high,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the elephant bull with large trunk,</l>
<l rend="indent4">resembling the small back of a forest man<note place="foot">The similarity between a man’s neck (if we understand <term xml:lang="ta">ciṟu-puṟam</term> as a lexeme) might be based on actual size, although in such a case we would rather expect a more direct word of comparison such as <term xml:lang="ta">pōl</term> or <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉa</term>.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">sounds lastingly inside the clefts,</l>
<l rend="indent3">being frightened by the arrows shot by the frenzied(?) bow.</l>
    </lg>
      </div>
